{
  "text": "Essentially, there are obvious distinctions between the two different distributive intentions in neural substrates. Previous clinical and neuroimaging studies have revealed the involvement of a distributed bihemispheric, corticosubcortical network in decision making [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) is an important part of this network [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and appears to be particularly involved in decision making when choices are ambiguous [CITATION_5] . This connection is of particular relevance in light of the growing evidence that this region is involved in risky decisions [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
